    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nvim.net.request is limited to GET requests\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n_Moved from [discussion](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/discussions/38944)_\n\n\nThe idea for this plan is to add a new API to the `vim.net` module that mirrors the Python `requests` library, providing direct HTTP method functions (`vim.net.get`, `vim.net.post`, etc.) that all call a modified version of `vim.net.request` function.\n\n## Current State\n\n- `vim.net.request(url, opts, on_response)` only supports GET requests\n- No body/post data support\n- No HTTP method parameter\n- Response only contains `body` field\n\n## New API\n\n### Signature Change\n\n```\nvim.net.request(method, url, opts, on_response)\n```\n\n| Parameter | Type | Required | Description |\n|-----------|------|----------|-------------|\n| method | string | Yes | HTTP method: GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE, HEAD, OPTIONS |\n| url | string | Yes | Target URL |\n| opts | vim.net.request.Opts | No | Request options |\n| on_response | fun(err?: string, response?: vim.net.request.Response) | No | Callback on completion |\n\nFor backwards compatibility we can have a local `request` function with the new signature and keep the current one marked as deprecated. All the new `vim.[verb]` methods will use the local function\n\n### `vim.net.request.Opts` Fields\n\n| Field | Type | Description |\n|-------|------|-------------|\n| body | string? | Request body to send (raw string) |\n| json | table? | Request body as JSON (auto-serializes, sets Content-Type) |\n| headers | table? | Custom headers to send |\n| outpath | string? | File path to save response body |\n| outbuf | integer? | Buffer to save response body |\n| retry | integer? | Number of retries on transient failures |\n\n\n### Response Fields\n\n| Field | Type | Description |\n|-------|------|-------------|\n| body | string | Response body content |\n| status | integer | HTTP status code |\n| headers | table | Response headers |\n\n### HTTP Status Constants\n\n```lua\nvim.net.STATUS_OK = 200\nvim.net.STATUS_CREATED = 201\nvim.net.STATUS_NO_CONTENT = 204\nvim.net.STATUS_MOVED_PERMANENTLY = 301\nvim.net.STATUS_FOUND = 302\nvim.net.STATUS_NOT_MODIFIED = 304\nvim.net.STATUS_BAD_REQUEST = 400\nvim.net.STATUS_UNAUTHORIZED = 401\nvim.net.STATUS_FORBIDDEN = 403\nvim.net.STATUS_NOT_FOUND = 404\nvim.net.STATUS_METHOD_NOT_ALLOWED = 405\nvim.net.STATUS_INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR = 500\nvim.net.STATUS_BAD_GATEWAY = 502\nvim.net.STATUS_SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE = 503\n```\n\n### Convenience Methods\n\nAll methods call `vim.net.request` under the hood:\n\n```lua\nvim.net.get(url, opts, on_response)       -- vim.net.request('GET', url, opts, on_response)\nvim.net.post(url, opts, on_response)      -- vim.net.request('POST', url, opts, on_response)\nvim.net.put(url, opts, on_response)      -- vim.net.request('PUT', url, opts, on_response)\nvim.net.patch(url, opts, on_response)    -- vim.net.request('PATCH', url, opts, on_response)\nvim.net.delete(url, opts, on_response)   -- vim.net.request('DELETE', url, opts, on_response)\nvim.net.head(url, opts, on_response)     -- vim.net.request('HEAD', url, opts, on_response)\nvim.net.options(url, opts, on_response)  -- vim.net.request('OPTIONS', url, opts, on_response)\n```\n\n## Implementation Notes\n\n1. Auto-set `Content-Type: application/json` when `opts.json` is used\n2. For `HEAD` requests, use curl's `-I` flag\n\n\nWould love to hear some thoughts on this plan. I am able to start small draft implementations for each part if you guys think it's worth it",
